IME/GME claim is for teaching claims: "Teaching hospitals receive a payment from Medicare for Indirect Medical Education (IME) and Graduate
Medical Education (GME) expenses. This payment helps to defray the added costs of maintaining teaching
programs. For traditional Medicare patients, the IME payment is automatically paid by Medicare when a claim is processed. " reference: http://www.besler.com/wp-content/uploads/IME-Recovery-Services-11-15.pdf

Non-Health Care Facility Point of Origin (Physician Referral) - The patient was admitted to this facility upon an order of a physician.
Clinical referral - The patient was admitted upon the recommendation of this facility's clinic physician.
HMO referral - Reserved for national assignment. (eff. 3/08) Prior to 3/08, HMO referral - The patient was admitted upon the recommendation of a health maintenance organization (HMO) physician.
Transfer from hospital (Different Facility) - The patient was admitted to this facility as a hospital transfer from an acute care facility where he or she was an inpatient.
Transfer from a skilled nursing facility (SNF) or Intermediate Care Facility (ICF) - The patient was admitted to this facility as a transfer from a SNF or ICF where he or she was a resident.

Transfer from another health care facility - The patient was admitted to this facility as a transfer from another type of health care facility not defined elsewhere in this code list where he or she was an inpatient.
Emergency room - The patient was admitted to this facility after receiving services in this facility's emergency room department. (Obsolete - eff. 7/1/10)

Court/law enforcement - The patient was admitted upon the direction of a court of law or upon the request of a law enforcement agency's representative. Includes transfers from incarceration facilities.
Information not available - The means by which the patient was admitted is not known.

Reserved for National Assignment. (eff. 3/08) Prior to 3/08 defined as: Transfer from a Critical Access Hospital - patient was admitted/referred to this facility as a transfer from a Critical Access Hospital.
Transfer from Another Home Health Agency - The patient was admitted to this home health agency as a transfer from another home health agency. (Discontinued July 1, 2010 - See Condition Code 47)
Readmission to Same Home Health Agency - The patient was readmitted to this home health agency within the same home health episode period. (Discontinued July 1, 2010)

Transfer from hospital inpatient in the same facility resulting in a separate claim to the payer - The patient was admitted to this facility as a transfer from hospital inpatient within this facility resulting in a separate claim to the payer.
Transfer from Ambulatory Surgery Center - The patient was admitted to this facility as a transfer from an ambulatory surgery center. (eff. 10/1/2007)
Transfer from Hospice and is under a Hospice Plan of Care or Enrolled in a Hospice Program - The patient was admitted to this facility as a transfer from a hospice. (eff. 10/1/2007)
Normal delivery - A baby delivered without complications. (Obsolete eff. 10/1/07)
Premature delivery - A baby delivered with time and/or weight factors qualifying it for premature status. (Obsolete eff. 10/1/07)
Sick baby - A baby delivered with medical complications, other than those relating to premature status. (Obsolete eff. 10/1/07)
Extramural birth - A baby delivered in a non-sterile environment. (Obsolete eff. 10/1/07)
